05476nam a22006855i 9781501764233DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1328136427  a97815017642337 a10.1515/97815017642332doi  a(DE-B1597)602081  a(OCoLC)1295617531  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJV1015b.S45 2023 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a323.609412231 aSelwood, Jacob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAt Kingdom's Edge :bThe Suriname Struggles of Jeronimy Clifford, English Subject /cJacob Selwood. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (252 p.) :b5 b&w halftones, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgment -- tNote on Spelling, Dates, and Translations -- tIntroduction: English Subjecthood at Kingdom’s Edge -- t1. Creating an English Suriname (1651–1667) -- t2. Staying English in Dutch Suriname (1667–1687) -- t3. The Glorious Revolution in Suriname (1688–1695) -- t4. Colonial Subjecthood in England and the Netherlands (1696–1737) -- t5. The Many Afterlives of Jeronimy Clifford (1737–1780) -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt Kingdom's Edge investigates how life in a conquered colony both revealed and shaped what it meant to be English outside of the British Isles. Considering the case of Jeronimy Clifford, who rose to become one of Suriname's richest planters, Jacob Selwood examines the mutual influence of race and subjecthood in the early modern world. Clifford was a child in Suriname when the Dutch, in 1667, wrested the South American colony from England soon after England seized control of New Netherland in North America. Across the arc of his life—from time in the tenuous English colony to prosperity as a slaveholding planter to a stint in debtors' prison in London—Clifford used all the tools at his disposal to elevate and secure his status. His English subjecthood, which he clung to as a wealthy planter in Dutch-controlled Suriname, was a ready means to exert political, legal, economic, and cultural authority. Clifford deployed it without hesitation, even when it failed to serve his interests. In 1695 Clifford left Suriname and, until his death, he tried to regain control over his abandoned plantation and its enslaved workers. His evocation of international treaties at times secured the support of the Crown. The English and Dutch governments' responses reveal competing definitions of belonging between and across empires, as well as the differing imperial political cultures with which claimants to rights and privileges had to contend. Clifford's case highlights the unresolved tensions about the meanings of colonial subjecthood, Anglo-Dutch relations, and the legacy of England's seventeenth-century empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenshipzGreat BritainxColoniesxHistoryy17th century. 0aCitizenshipzGreat BritainxColoniesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical rightszGreat BritainxColoniesxHistoryy17th century. 0aPolitical rightszGreat BritainxColoniesxHistoryy18th century. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  adutch suriname, Interaction between English and dutch empires, english colonies conquered by other countries, english subjecthood, when did the netherlands conquer surinam, dutch colonialism and empire.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311